\begin_layout Standard
A ``waveguide'' is a structure that allows waves to propagate along one
 (or more) direction(s) while confining them in one or more other 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

transverse
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 directions.
 These arise in many forms in many different wave equations, with a variety
 of mechanisms for the transverse confinement: silica optical fibers, sound
 waves propagating down hollow tubes, coaxial transmission lines, and so
 forth.
 One commonplace confinement mechanism is known as 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

total internal reflection
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

index guiding
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

