\begin_layout Section
Review of scalar waves
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In these notes, we consider the scalar wave equation:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
-\hat{A}u=c^{2}\nabla^{2}u=\frac{\partial^{2}u}{\partial t^{2}},
\]

\end_inset

where the coefficient 
\begin_inset Formula $c(\vec{x})>0$
\end_inset

, which has units of speed, is some function of 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{x}$
\end_inset

 and we have defined the linear operator 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{A}=-c^{2}\nabla^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 It is straightforward to show that 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{A}$
\end_inset

 is Hermitian (i.e.
 self-adjoint, 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{A}=\hat{A}^{*}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $*$
\end_inset

 denotes the adjoint) and positive semidefinite under a variety of boundary
 conditions on 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 (e.g.
 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 or its normal derivative vanishes at the boundary of the domain) with the
 inner product 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle u,v\rangle=\int\frac{\bar{u}v}{c^{2}}$
\end_inset

 (where 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{u}$
\end_inset

 denote complex conjugation), i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle u,\hat{A}v\rangle=\langle\hat{A}u,v\rangle$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle u,\hat{A}u\rangle=\int|\nabla u|^{2}\le0$
\end_inset

 for all
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Or rather, for all 
\begin_inset Formula $u,v$
\end_inset

 in the appropriate Sobolev space for this problem, which basically means
 that we restrict ourselves to functions where these integrals are defined.
 In these notes, I won't worry about pinning down the precise function spaces.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $u,v$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For reasonable 
\begin_inset Formula $c(\vec{x})$
\end_inset

