\end_layout

\end_inset

 i.e.
 a complete basis of eigenfunctions for 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{A}$
\end_inset

, and to understand the solution of the wave equation it is enough to understand
 the eigenfunctions
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
In an infinite domain, functional analysts would call some of these solutions
 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

generalized
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 eigenfunctions.
 e.g.
 if 
\begin_inset Formula $c=1$
\end_inset

 on an infinite domain, the solutions are planewaves 
\begin_inset Formula $u=e^{i\vec{k}\cdot\vec{x}}$
\end_inset

 for real vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{k}$
\end_inset

 (disallowing solutions that grow exponentially at infinity), but these
 are not normalizable: 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle u,u\rangle$
\end_inset

 diverges, and 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 lives in a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

rigged
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 Hilbert space rather than a Hilbert space.
 I will gloss over this and similar distinctions.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $u(\vec{x})$
\end_inset

 satisfying 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{A}u=\lambda u$
\end_inset

.
 It is easy to show that the self-adjointness means that 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 will be real, and the positive-semidefiniteness means that 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda\geq0$
\end_inset

, so it is convenient to write 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda=\omega^{2}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

 is real with units of frequency.
 Plugging this back into the wave equation, we see that 
\begin_inset Formula $-\hat{A}u=-\omega^{2}u=\ddot{u}$
\end_inset

 and hence each eigensolution describes oscillating modes 
\begin_inset Formula $u(\vec{x})e^{\pm i\omega t}$
\end_inset

 with (eigen)frequency 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

.
 These are the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

normal modes:
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 another consequence of self-adjointness is that eigensolutions are 
\emph on
orthogonal
\emph default
: given 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{A}u_{1}=\omega_{1}^{2}u_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{A}u_{2}=\omega_{2}^{2}u_{2}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{1}^{2}\neq\omega_{2}^{2}$
\end_inset

, it is easy to show that 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle u_{1},u_{2}\rangle=0$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 is a constant (homogeneous 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

), the eigensolutions yield the planewaves 
\begin_inset Formula $u(\vec{x},t)=e^{i(\vec{k}\cdot\vec{x}-\omega t)}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega(\vec{k})=\pm c|\vec{k}|$
\end_inset

, in which case 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 is the magnitude of both the phase velocity (
\begin_inset Formula $\omega/|\vec{k}|$
\end_inset

) and the group velocity (
\begin_inset Formula $|\nabla_{k}\omega|$
\end_inset

): it is the speed at which waves travel and information propagates.
 For the case of inhomogeneous 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 considered below, the solutions and hence the velocities are more complicated,
 but we can still in some sense think of smaller-
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 regions as being 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

slower
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 materials.
\end_layout

