\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{1}(k)$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $<c_{0}|k|$
\end_inset

, and hence is guided (exponentially decaying in 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{0}$
\end_inset

).
 To do this, we don't actually need to 
\emph on
compute
\emph default
 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{1}$
\end_inset

, we only need to find an 
\emph on
upper bound
\emph default
 for 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{1}$
\end_inset

 and show that this bound is 
\begin_inset Formula $<c_{0}|k|$
\end_inset

.
 The key to finding an upper bound is the 
\series bold
min--max theorem
\series default
, also known as the 
\series bold
variational theorem
\series default
: for any self-adjoint operator 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{A}_{k}$
\end_inset

 , it is easy to show
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Landau77:QM,JoannopoulosJo08-book"

\end_inset

 that the smallest eigenvalue 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{1}^{2}$
\end_inset

 minimizes the Rayleigh quotient 
\begin_inset Formula $R\{u\}=\langle u,\hat{A}_{k}u\rangle/\langle u,u\rangle$
\end_inset

 over all 
\begin_inset Formula $u(x)$
\end_inset

, and in particular that 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{1}^{2}\leq R\{u\}$
\end_inset

 for 
\emph on
any
\emph default
 
\begin_inset Formula $u(x)$
\end_inset

.
 Hence, we just need to find 
\emph on
some
\emph default
 
\begin_inset Formula $u(x)$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $R\{u\}<c_{0}^{2}k^{2}$
\end_inset

 and it will follow that 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{1}<c_{0}|k|$
\end_inset

: that a guided mode exists.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Multiplying both sides of 
\begin_inset Formula $R\{u\}<c_{0}^{2}k^{2}$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle u,u\rangle$
\end_inset

 and integrating the numerator 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle u,\hat{A}_{k}u\rangle$
\end_inset

 once by parts, we obtain 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\int_{-\infty}^{\infty}\left(|u'|^{2}+k^{2}|u|^{2}\right)dx<c_{0}^{2}k^{2}\int_{-\infty}^{\infty}\frac{|u|^{2}}{c^{2}}dx.
\]

\end_inset

Now, if we can find 
\emph on
some
\emph default
 function 
\begin_inset Formula $u(x)$
\end_inset

 for which this inequality is true, we are done.
 It turns out that there are many choices of 
\begin_inset Formula $u(x)$
\end_inset

 that will work, but one of the easiest is 
\begin_inset Formula $u(x)=e^{-|x|/L}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 is a free parameter that we can choose to enforce the inequality.
 Before we do this, let us be more precise about 
\begin_inset Formula $c(x)$
\end_inset

.
 We could use this technique to analyze the specific piecewise-constant
 
\begin_inset Formula $c(x)$
\end_inset

 from the previous section, but it turns out that we can prove localization
 for a much wider range of 
\begin_inset Formula $c(x)$
\end_inset

 functions.
 In particular, we write 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{1}{c(x)^{2}}=\frac{1}{c_{0}^{2}}+\Delta(x),
\]

\end_inset

so that 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta(x)>0\Leftrightarrow c(x)<c_{0}$
\end_inset

.
 We will allow 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta(x)$
\end_inset

 to be 
\emph on
any
\emph default
 function as long as there is a localized 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

slow
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 (
\begin_inset Formula $c<c_{0}$
\end_inset

) region 
\emph on
on average
\emph default
, as defined by the following two conditions: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\int_{-\infty}^{\infty}\Delta(x)\, dx>0\qquad\mbox{(slow on average)},
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\int_{-\infty}^{\infty}|\Delta(x)|\, dx<\infty\qquad\mbox{(\ensuremath{c\neq c_{0}}is localized)}.
\]

\end_inset

We will now show that these two conditions are sufficient to imply that
 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{1}(k)<c_{0}|k|$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $k\neq0$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Plugging this 
\begin_inset Formula $1/c^{2}$
\end_inset

 into our desired inequality on 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

, we immediately see that the 
\begin_inset Formula $k^{2}|u|^{2}$
\end_inset

 terms cancel on both sides.
 Computing the integral 
\begin_inset Formula $\int|u'|^{2}dx=\frac{2}{L^{2}}\int_{0}^{\infty}e^{-2x/L}=\frac{1}{L}$
\end_inset

, we are left with: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{1}{L}<c_{0}^{2}k^{2}\int_{-\infty}^{\infty}\Delta(x)\, e^{-2|x|/L}dx.
\]

\end_inset

For any 
\begin_inset Formula $k\neq0$
\end_inset

, this is true for a sufficiently large choice of 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

.
 To show this, it suffices to show that the inequality holds in the limit
 
\begin_inset Formula $L\to\infty$
\end_inset

.
 The limit of the left-hand side is 0, while the limit of the right hand
 side is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\lim_{L\to\infty}c_{0}^{2}k^{2}\int_{-\infty}^{\infty}\Delta(x)\, e^{-2|x|/L}dx=c_{0}^{2}k^{2}\int_{-\infty}^{\infty}\Delta(x)\,\lim_{L\to\infty}e^{-2|x|/L}dx=c_{0}^{2}k^{2}\int_{-\infty}^{\infty}\Delta(x)\, dx.
\]

\end_inset

Interchanging limits and integration is not allowed in general, but it is
 okay under various conditions on the integrand that one can look up in
 analysis textbooks.
 In this case, it is okay because of something called 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Lebesgue's dominated convergence theorem
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Rudin87"

\end_inset

.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
In particular, you can interchange limits and integration for 
\begin_inset Formula $\int f(x)$
\end_inset

 when 
\begin_inset Formula $|f(x)|\leq g(x)$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $g(x)$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\int g(x)<\infty$
\end_inset

.
 In this case 
\begin_inset Formula $|\Delta(x)\, e^{-2|x|/L}|\leq|\Delta(x)|$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\int|\Delta|<\infty$
\end_inset

 by our assumption of a localized slow region.
 
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Thus, in the 
\begin_inset Formula $L\to\infty$
\end_inset

 limit, our inequality becomes
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
0<c_{0}^{2}k^{2}\int_{-\infty}^{\infty}\Delta(x)\, dx,
\]

\end_inset

which is true for 
\begin_inset Formula $k\ne0$
\end_inset

 due to our assumption 
\begin_inset Formula $\int\Delta>0.$
\end_inset

 If the inequality holds for 
\begin_inset Formula $L\to\infty$
\end_inset

, then it must also hold for some sufficiently large (but finite) 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

.
 Hence, there exists a 
\begin_inset Formula $u(x)$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{1}(k)^{2}\leq R\{u\}<c_{0}^{2}k^{2}$
\end_inset

 and hence we have at least one guided mode with a frequency 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{1}$
\end_inset

 below the light cone.
