\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There are many wave-localization problems that can be subjected to a similar
 analysis, such as waveguiding in Maxwell's equations
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "BambergerBo90,LeeAv08"

\end_inset

 or localized states of a potential well (
\begin_inset Formula $\int V<0$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\int|V|<\infty$
\end_inset

) in the SchrÃ¶dinger operator 
\begin_inset Formula $-\nabla^{2}+V(\vec{x})$
\end_inset

 of quantum mechanics
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Landau77:QM"

\end_inset

.
 For the SchrÃ¶dinger operator 
\begin_inset Formula $-\nabla^{2}+V(\vec{x})$
\end_inset

, one similarly wants to show 
\begin_inset Formula $\int|\nabla u|^{2}<-\int|u|^{2}V$
\end_inset

 for some trial function 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 in order to prove that the eigenvalue is negative (hence localized if 
\begin_inset Formula $V\to0$
\end_inset

 for large 
\begin_inset Formula $|x|$
\end_inset

), so by comparison we see that 
\begin_inset Formula $-\Delta$
\end_inset

 in the wave equation above is playing the role of a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

potential well.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The fact that the proof in the previous section was so easy (at the level
 of an undergraduate homework problem
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Landau77:QM"

\end_inset

), and would have worked for almost any reasonable choice of 
\begin_inset Formula $u(x)$
\end_inset

 where we have a parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 to control the localization length, is essentially the consequence of a
 scaling relationship.
 Slightly rewritten, we wanted to show 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\int|\nabla u|^{2}}{\int|u|^{2}}<c_{0}^{2}k^{2}\frac{\int|u|^{2}\Delta}{\int|u|^{2}}.
\]

\end_inset

Suppose that 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta\ne0$
\end_inset

 only in some region of diameter 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $u=\psi(\vec{x}/L)$
\end_inset

 for some square-integrable function 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi$
\end_inset

 (so that 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 controls the lengthscale as above).
 Then the left-hand side scales as 
\begin_inset Formula $1/L^{2}$
\end_inset

, while the right-hand side scales as 
\begin_inset Formula $h/L$
\end_inset

 (the fraction of 
\begin_inset Formula $|u|^{2}$
\end_inset

 in the 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta\ne0$
\end_inset

 region).
 Therefore, it is obvious that the inequality must hold for a sufficiently
 large 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

.
 In general, the consequence is that 
\emph on
localization is easy in one dimension
\emph default
---even for an arbitrarily weak 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

potential well
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 (small 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta$
\end_inset

 and/or small 
\begin_inset Formula $k^{2}$
\end_inset

), one always has a localized eigenfunction, a familiar theorem in quantum
 mechanics.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In higher dimensions, however, the same scaling comparison tells us that
 matters are different.
 In 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

 dimensions, the left-hand side still scales as 
\begin_inset Formula $1/L^{2}$
\end_inset

, but the right-hand side scales as 
\begin_inset Formula $(h/L)^{d}$
\end_inset

.
 This means that for 
\begin_inset Formula $d>2$
\end_inset

 it is 
\emph on
not
\emph default
 advantageous to have a large 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

, so weak localization does not occur.
 For dimensions 
\begin_inset Formula $>2$
\end_inset

, you must have a sufficiently strong 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

potential well
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 in order to localize a solution, again a well-known fact in quantum mechanics
 but true in other areas as well.
 For 
\begin_inset Formula $d=2$
\end_inset

, both sides of the inequality scale in the same way with 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

, which tells us that two dimensions is a borderline case that requires
 a more delicate analysis.
\end_layout

